---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import SpecSection from "../components/SpecSection.astro";
import FeatureRow from "../components/FeatureRow.astro";
---
<Layout
  title="TermCoder — features"
  description="Everything TermCoder does: no API key, model routing, memory and retrieval, an embedded terminal, autonomous mode, sub-agents and skills, and a built-in study tutor."
  active="features.html"
>
  <SpecSection gutter="//">
    <div class="t full">
      <div class="mono-eyebrow"><span class="slash">//</span> FEATURES</div>
      <h2>Everything it does.</h2>
      <p>One agent loop, a lot of surface. Every capability below is in the shipping build — no roadmap
        items dressed up as features.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="a full">
      <div class="feat-grid">
        <FeatureRow k="// no key">
          <h3>Runs with no API key</h3>
          <p>Open a folder and start — TermCoder ships with a free, keyless model, so there's no sign-up, card, or quota to configure. When the free tier is busy it retries and falls back on its own, and <code class="mono">/upgrade</code> connects a free Gemini key in two steps when you want more.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// terminal-first">
          <h3>Built for the terminal</h3>
          <p>Slash commands, @file mentions to pull code into context, a live model picker, multi-line input with word-jump editing, and a trust prompt the first time you open a folder. Nothing leaves the keyboard.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// any model">
          <h3>Any model, or fully local</h3>
          <p>Bring Anthropic, OpenAI, or Google Gemini with your own key, or point it at a local model through Ollama and run with no account and no data leaving your machine. Switch models mid-session with <code class="mono">/model</code>.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// modes">
          <h3>Build and Plan modes</h3>
          <p>Plan mode reads the code and proposes an approach without touching a single file; Build mode carries the change out, asking permission before anything that writes or runs. Toggle with <code class="mono">shift+tab</code>.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// termcoder/auto">
          <h3>A brain that reviews itself</h3>
          <p>The default <code class="mono">termcoder/auto</code> routes each task by difficulty — a fast model for simple edits, a stronger one for hard work — then reviews its own diff before finishing and fixes what it flags.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// autonomous">
          <h3>Works unattended</h3>
          <p>Hand it a goal with <code class="mono">/background</code> and it plans, edits, and runs your project's tests, feeding failures back and fixing until the check passes or it runs out of rounds. Every round is checkpointed, so you can revert.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// specialists">
          <h3>Sub-agents and skills</h3>
          <p>Hand focused work to specialist sub-agents — reviewer, tester, debugger, architect — with the <code class="mono">$</code> key. Reusable skill playbooks load on demand, so idle skills cost nothing.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// github backbone">
          <h3>Sync, share, and packs</h3>
          <p>Sync your settings, drafts, and study decks across machines through a private gist. Share a session as a link anyone can open. Bundle your agents, skills, and commands into a pack, and install someone else's with <code class="mono">/pack install</code> — all on GitHub, no server to run.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// classrooms">
          <h3>Classrooms for teachers and students</h3>
          <p>A teacher creates a class, students join with a link, and assignments and submissions ride GitHub comments. Shared packs install on join, so everyone starts with the same agents and skills. Async by design — nothing to host.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// anywhere">
          <h3>Terminal, desktop, or browser</h3>
          <p>Run the CLI, the desktop app, or open the full interface in a browser from a local <code class="mono">termcoder serve</code> — the same engine everywhere. Shared sessions open in a hosted viewer with just the link.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// token economy">
          <h3>Kind to your context</h3>
          <p>Old tool output is elided from the model's context and long results are capped, so a long session stops re-billing everything it has already read. A context meter shows you how full the window is.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// study mode">
          <h3>A study companion inside</h3>
          <p>Switch to the termexplorer model and the same tool becomes a patient tutor for schoolwork — explaining, summarizing, and building flashcards. <a class="mono" style="color:var(--color-accent)" href="study.html">See study mode →</a></p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// memory">
          <h3>It remembers</h3>
          <p>Facts you tell it once — your stack, your conventions, the thing that always breaks — persist across sessions, so you stop re-explaining your own project.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// retrieval">
          <h3>It reads before it answers</h3>
          <p>A symbol index and a repo map let it find where something is defined and how the project fits together, instead of guessing from the file you happened to open.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// terminal">
          <h3>A real shell, inside the app</h3>
          <p>The desktop app embeds a terminal. It detects the coding CLIs on your PATH — Claude Code, Codex, Gemini — and launches any of them in one click, in your project folder.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
        <FeatureRow k="// sign in">
          <h3>Use a plan you already pay for</h3>
          <p>Sign in with Claude Pro/Max or ChatGPT Plus/Pro instead of buying API credits. Experimental: it uses the vendors' own login flows, and those can change without notice.</p>
        </FeatureRow>
      </div>
    </div>
  </SpecSection>

  <SpecSection gutter="—">
    <div class="t full">
      <div class="stats">
        <div class="stat"><b>16</b><span>capabilities, all shipping</span></div>
        <div class="stat"><b>16</b><span>builtin tools</span></div>
        <div class="stat"><b><span class="em">$</span>0</b><span>free to start</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="row-2">
        <a class="btn-2 go" href="download.html">Download the app</a>
        <a class="btn-2" href="install.html">Install the CLI</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </SpecSection>
</Layout>
